# .env.example — Template for .devcontainer/.env
#
# The actual .env is generated automatically by initializeCommand.sh
# and is NEVER committed to git.
#
# ── How to make credentials survive codespace recreation ──────────────────────
# By default, N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY is randomly generated each time a new
# codespace is created. If the codespace is DELETED (not just suspended),
# a new key is generated and existing n8n credentials become unreadable.
#
# To avoid this, set N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY as a GitHub Codespaces Secret:
#   GitHub → Your Repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Codespaces
#   → New repository secret → Name: N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY
#   → Value: (run `openssl rand -hex 32` locally to generate one)
#
# initializeCommand.sh will use the secret value instead of generating a
# random one, keeping your credentials stable across codespace recreations.

# Encryption key for n8n credentials storage.
# WARNING: Changing this after credentials have been saved will make them
# permanently unreadable. Never rotate this key without re-entering all creds.
N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY=

# Public base URL for n8n webhooks.
# Set automatically to the Codespaces forwarded URL when running in Codespaces,
# or http://localhost:5678/ when running locally.
WEBHOOK_URL=
